          <p id="ISA.IO.94">
      ISA was established in accordance with the binding 1982 
      <xr pageref="N" ref="UNCLOS.IO.1">United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea (UNCLOS)</xr>
      , which provides a regulatory framework for the use and protection of the high seas and international seabed. ISA functions as an autonomous international organization in relationship with the UN. The Authority administers access to the resources of the international seabed `Area’ (which is defined as the seabed and subsoil beyond the limits of national jurisdiction).
    </p>
          <int-org-section id="IO.ISA.01" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Members</heading>
               <p>
        There are 169 members (168 member states and the European Union); in addition there are 29 observer states and territories and 69 observer organizations. All states parties to 
        <xr pageref="N" ref="UNCLOS.IO.1">UNCLOS</xr>
         are members of ISA.
      </p>
          </int-org-section>
     </int-org-block>
     <int-org-section id="ISA.IO.451" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
          <heading>Organization</heading>
          <heading-note>April 2024</heading-note>
          <int-org-section id="ISA.IO.452" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Assembly</heading>
               <p id="ISA.IO.428">The Assembly is the supreme organ of the Authority, consisting of representatives of all member states who gather for an annual session, usually in July. In conjunction with the Council, it formulates the Authority's general policies. It elects Council members and members of the Finance Committee, and approves the Authority’s budget.</p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="ISA.IO.453" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Council</heading>
               <p id="ISA.IO.429">The Council, elected by the Assembly for four-year terms, acts as the executive organ of the Authority. It consists of 36 members, comprising the four states that are the largest importers or consumers of seabed minerals, the four largest investors in seabed minerals, the four major exporters of seabed minerals, six developing countries representing special interests, and 18 members covering all the geographical regions. In 2024 the 29th annual session of the Council was to be convened in two parts (in March, and July-August).</p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="ISA.IO.454" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Legal and Technical Commission</heading>
               <p id="ISA.IO.430">The Legal and Technical Commission, comprising 24 experts elected by the Council for five-year terms, holds two sessions each year. It makes recommendations concerning seabed activities, assesses the environmental implications of extraction activities in the Area, proposes measures to protect the marine environment, and reviews the execution of exploration contracts.</p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="ISA.IO.455" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Finance Committee</heading>
               <p id="ISA.IO.431">The Committee, comprising 15 experts, was established to make recommendations to the Assembly and the Council on all financial and budgetary issues.</p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="ISA.IO.456" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Secretariat</heading>
               <p id="ISA.IO.432">The secretariat provides administrative services to all the bodies of the Authority and implements the relevant work programmes. It comprises Offices of the Secretary-General, Environmental Management and Mineral Resources, Legal Affairs, and Administration Services.</p>
               <p>Under the terms of the 1994 Agreement Relating to the Implementation of Part XI of the Convention, the secretariat provisionally was to perform the functions of the Enterprise, the organ through which the Authority carries out deep seabed mining operations (directly or through joint ventures). It was headed by a Special Representative of the Secretary-General during the period 2018-23, and by an Interim Director-General from January 2024.</p>
